KEEP IT SIMPLE [BLUE & YELLOW], 2022

Acrylic Paint, Glitter & Resin On Birch Panel
122 cm x 122 cm 

If it hasn’t become evident through the recurrence of this mantra in my work, it is one of my favourite perspectives to reiterate. 
I believe that genius lies in the ability to extract the simple truths from complex problems… To grow, to find clarity, to create peace of mind, to create discipline, action and overall to seize the day… all can be rooted back to extracting the simple truths of what’s important and needed for each of us at any given moment.

In this painting, I tried to reflect this by practicing restraint from adding anything beyond what is necessary to portray this message.

How do YOU meditate???

I believe it comes in many forms and can be channeled through anything that brings me into a state of flow. A good conversation, a hard workout, eyes closed in a park, paint on a canvas… there are endless opportunities for presence and stillness everyday.

A kind reminder to stay open and the wonders of this world will happily provide you with a little bit of peace and guidance 🙏

Unless you’re some type of god, there’s no way to know all the answers, all the outcomes or all the solutions in life. 

But, I believe that that unknown is what universally connects us all as humans. 

Each day we get to show up, set our aims and do the best we can with what we have. 

Whether in creativity, relationships, health, career, etc… the same applies. 

And the magic of this, is that it forces is us to find the miracles of the moment. 
“Now” is all we ever have.

Let go of what you can’t control, focus on what you can and JUST KEEP GOING.

That’s my stream of consciousness for today thanks for reading lol

Follow for more of my thought processing through art 🙏

3 important lessons I’ve learnt as full time artist:

👉 Not everyone’s advice is valuable. How one person succeeded isn’t always relevant to your journey, but learning to discern between the two is paramount.

👉 Mistakes & failures are necessary. Being able to see the lessons and possibly the new opportunities when things don’t go your way has been key to staying curious, engaged and minimizing burnout. 

👉 Expression of personal creative interests is far more fulfilling than trying to demonstrate skill & proficiency. There’s always someone more skilled, there’s never another you. And I have a hunch that the only way to play the long game in the arts is to do YOU, not try to be someone else.

Featured is “The Money Series”, a collection that started as a previous show concept focused as a meditative process for me to explore my own relationship between wants and needs… or the tension between financial & spiritual fulfillment.

How to not get creatively stuck as a creator:
1. Define the vision of your project
2. Set the parameters & limitations of your materials, colors, subject matter, etc.
3. Set a deadline and work backwards to create a timeline of how much space is approximately needed for each piece.
4. Let the creative juices flow and send it!!!

This might not work for everybody, but a clear vision helps me not get lost in the endless abyss of new ideas and focus in on actually getting one idea done vs a bunch “half done”. Especially since I like to work in collections where a dialogue can be continued throughout…

The theorems written throughout the layers of this painting represent a method used in math & science to determine:
If a problem has a solution
If that solution is unique

I found the framework can be related to daily reality in the following ways:

Do the problems I’m stuck on have a solution? Am I focusing on what I can control? Is this really a problem or have I made it up in my mind?
Am I stuck on thinking about one singular outcome when there could be other avenues towards resolution? Is the solution I want the only solution? Or, alternatively, is the solution I want even the solution I need?

Title: Love Is All There Is… If You Disagree, I Hate You…
Date: 2021
Size: 183 cm x 122 cm
Material: Acrylic Paint & Coffee On Canvas

About the work:
This piece was part of a solo exhibition entitled, “An Exploration Of Mickey”. The concept of using Mickey to such an extent was to create an inviting and disarming access point, so that the dialogue could focus on the relationship between the featured quotes and imagery with fewer barriers of intimidation for the everyday viewer. The featured quote is a statement I have used in previous works as a commentary on the hypocrisy I see in the actions of many public figures.  As in, “everyone claims to be compassionate, understanding and willing to change until they’re actually confronted to do so in a way outside their comfort zone.”

The idea for this piece, the show and subsequent works from this series was prompted by the controversial artist, Richard Prince. Though I have mixed feelings about his methods of recontextualizing other peoples work, I was curious to explore how it would feel to exploit something that wasn’t mine. Using Disney felt like a valid muse, as it is the source of both positivity and controversy in mainstream culture. 

Audio is @artistgeorgecondo

Title: Ask For What You Want…
Date: November 4, 2022
Size: 122 cm x 152.4 cm
Material: Motion Picture Prop Money, Acrylic Paint & Machine Cut Vinyl, Epoxy Resin blended with glitter on a birch panel.

About the work: 
Aimed to prompt feelings of courage and self-belief, “Ask For What You Want…”, is based off a note that frequented my personal journal during a period of transition from corporate life to a self employed life.  There is often a gap between my desires to “have” the material successes, and the willingness I experience to “be” the person that can “do” the actions to receive the praise of providing value through action. 

When I observe this at a societal level, money & power are generally at the epicentre of human desire and I see this creating internal tension between material & spiritual fulfilment in life. On one level, I see this piece as a visual prompt to inspire the observer to close the gap between future desire and the necessary present action… and on another level, I see this piece as a commentary questioning whether the values held at the center of modern western culture are healthy or damaging to society as a whole as well as to an individuals ability to experience fulfilment. 

#popart #contemporaryart #inspirationalquotes

Title: The Thrill Of The Risk
Date: 2023
Size: 91.5 cm x 122 cm
Material: Acrylic & Spray Paint On Canvas

About The Work:
Aimed at being a snapshot of the American dream and all that can be involved in the pursuit of the Hollywood definition of the “good life”. The imagery featured pays homage to American “blue collar” art forms such as the pulp art magazines of the 50’s, tattoo flash and the early American  brands (Champion logo featured in yellow). This series serves as an exploration of different styles of art that have emerged within pop culture over the years.

As previously mentioned, the intent with much of my work is to create visual prompts to serve as positive buffers from the noise of external influences.  It would seem to be human nature to over complicate various situations, when the reality may be much simpler.  I tried to lean in to this more than I am comfortable with by keeping this piece limited to two colors and loosely painting the lettering of the text using one department store brush. The piece is also my attempt to pay homage to artist, Ed Ruscha, who has served as a large influence in my attraction towards text in paintings. The colors and simplicity reference his 1964 painting, “Hurting The Word Radio #2”.

A practice of love over ego.
Letting go of self-constructed narratives to live for universal betterment through love & acceptance of life’s fluidity.
To me, this phrase represents a practice in humility & compassion… which would seem to be the difference between “solution focused progression” over “problem centric stagnation”. 

Though undoubtedly a lifelong pursuit to embody, I’d say it’s a valuable northstar nonetheless. ✨

2023

Exploring a more traditional approach to figure painting, this work served as a collaborative journey with @mischawise. It was an attempt to capture the interplay between vulnerability and seduction. 
The phrase reinterprets a bible verse, guiding it into a statement of self-love and feminine empowerment. It aims to celebrate the strength found in the embrace of one’s vulnerabilities, and the inner power that can come from such acceptance.
